    : never // Actual can be undefined but not Expected: forbid the field
  : NonNullableExact<NonNullable<Expected>, NonNullable<Actual>>;

export type ExactResponse<Expected, Actual> = Expected &
  Actual & // Needed to infer `Actual`
  (null extends Actual
    ? null extends Expected
      ? Actual extends null // If only null stop here, because NonNullable<null> = never
        ? null
        : CheckUndefined<Expected, Actual>
      : never // Actual can be null but not Expected: forbid the field
    : CheckUndefined<Expected, Actual>);
```

# Proposal

## The problem 

First of all, the current behavior comes with great implications for those of us who aim for full type safety. Why? Take `Object.keys` for example, it yields a type `string`. This is highly inconvenient, as it impacts our productivity on one of the most common operation - accessing with an index in a loop. This is also a common source of mistakes since we almost always end up doing unsafe type casts/assertions (ironically).

I have an example here that shows how pernicious this is. Let's say that we have an object called `fns` that is a map of functions that return `string`s. Simple. Now we want to `concat` the returns of all these functions. That's when type safety comes at a high cost:

<details>
<summary>Details</summary>

```ts
const fns = {
    a: () => 'hello, ',
    b: () => 'how are',
    c: 'you?',
};

const concatFnsResults = (fns: {a: () => string, b: () => string}) => {
    reduce(Object.keys(fns), (acc, key) => {
        if (typeof fns[key as keyof typeof fns] === 'function') {
            const fnResult = fns[key as keyof typeof fns]();

            if (typeof fnResult === 'string') {
                return `${acc}${fnResult}`;
            }
        }

        return '';
    }, '');
};
```
</details>

As you can see, because types are not exact, we end up double checking everything at runtime. To me, this is a very basic operation that should not be so time consuming. Imagine if it was a more complex scenario? There must be something we can do, TypeScript could have checked this.

**But exact types were discussed long and wide, and the introduction of new semantics will not bring us closer to a solution, as @RyanCavanaugh explained very well.** But what if we took the problem the other way around?

## Possible solution

### Intro 

The solution I propose is not easy and might even get rejected, but I will go ahead. While it is true that we could pass a `Point3D` as a `Point2D`, this is unsound and most of the times we would like to have the exact types. Ultimately, this is very implementation-dependent. For instance, if you are going to use `Object.keys` then it is likely that you'll want the exact types, and in the case of `Point2D/3D`, you don't care and you'd like to allow it.

### Semantics

In short, we need to introduce a compiler option that will disallow extra properties - that will make everything to be exact. 
But once we have everything exact by default, how do we re-write our `Point2D/3D` example?

```ts
const fnInexact = (point2d: ~Point2D) => {};

fnInexact({a: 1, b: 2, c: 3}) // works
fnInexact({a: 1, b: 2, c: 3} as Point3D) // works

const fnExact = (point2d: Point2D) => {};

fnExact({a: 1, b: 2, c: 3}) // error
fnExact({a: 1, b: 2, c: 3} as Point3D) // error
```

<details>
<summary>See Point2D/3D</summary>

```ts
type Point2D = {
    a: number,
    b: number
};

type Point3D = {
    a: number,
    b: number,
    c: number
};
```

</details>

I like `~` because it indicates that a type will tolerate extra properties. **Thanks to this, we can finally reconciliate with `keyof`**. Doing `keyof Point2D` will yield `'a' | 'b'`, while doing `keyof ~Point2D` will yield `string | number`.

With this, we could rewrite `Object.keys` like the following:

```ts
declare function keys<O>(object: O): `${keyof O & (string | number)}`;
```

## Conclusion

It was said many times that it's unclear which types are exact or inexact. In today's type system, the only types that are checked to be exact are object literals. In other words, all types are inexact. Even if we introduced some `Exact` or `{| ... |}`, it would be impossible to control the flow of exact types. Why? Because as soon as they passed through a function that did not use `Exact` or `{| ... |}`, they would become inexact again.

For this reason, I believe that we should make all types exact and allow for `~` to signal whether extra properties can be tolerated/handled or not. This way, a type marked with `~` can flow through the analysis without getting swallowed.

Thanks to this, a function implementation (or type) is free to choose what it is able to handle.

### This has serious implications?

Yes. This absolutely needs to be enabled by a compiler flag. This is a breaking change.
When the flag is disabled, `~` is ignored on the types that use it (the current behavior).

### So which types are inexact?

Any types that are found with `~`. This means `extends` will keep types exact:

```ts
function fn0<T extends {n: number}>(p: T): number;

fn0({n: 1})         // works
fn0({n: 1, x: 2})   // error
```

And we could write the inexact counterpart of this, where two forms are allowed:

```ts
function fn1<T extends ~{n: number}>(p: T): number;
function fn2<T extends {n: number}>(p: ~T): number;

fn1({n: 1})         // works
fn1({n: 1, x: 2})   // works

fn2({n: 1})         // works
fn2({n: 1, x: 2})   // works
```

### Assignability

Given a type `T`:
- `T` is assignable to `~T`
- `~T` is not assignable to `T`
- `~T & T` is assignable to `~T`
- `~T & T` is not assignable to `T`

