# Take 2

Reading through this thread, it is clear that a few unrelated topics have all been combined here.

The only thing I want to ask for is `Exact Object Types`.

What does this mean: When passing a value to a position where an object type is expected, extra keys should give you an error. This can be done with no syntax additions since there is already syntax to allow extra keys in any object type.

Consider something as simple as:
```ts
type Person = {
    name: string,
    age: number,
};

function helloPerson(person: Person) {}

helloPerson({
    name: 'Naman',
    age: 30,
    // Errors as expected
    location: 'San Francisco'
})

const person = {
    name: 'Naman',
    age: 30,
    location: 'San Francisco'
};

// No Error! What!!
helloPerson(person);
```

I would expect both the function calls to error. What's worse is that the current Typescript behavior is simply inconsistent. Sometimes it allows extra keys and sometimes it doesn't. It doesn't make sense that EPC only checks object literals but not variables defined right next to the function call.

## My proposal

Since Typescript doesn't allow setting options locally, any change in semantics is going to cause huge fragmentation. So instead we have to come up with changes that are purely additive.

We can start adding Negated Type #29317

This would make it possible to define any string except a certain set of strings:

```ts
type Exclude<A, B> = A & not B;
```

This in turn would enable a Utility Type to define exact object types:

```ts
type Exact<Obj extends {}> = {[k: Exclude<string, keyof Obj>]: never} & Obj;
```

We could stop here, but it important for the semantics of `keyof` to keep working correctly exact object types. (it should not return `string`)

So Typescript needs built-in support for Exact objects.

To enable this, we add new syntax, which is the same syntax as Flow:
```ts
type Person = {| name: string, age: number |};
```

NOTE: This syntax is **only** for objects. The pipes only get this new meaning directly inside the curly brackets of an object type. There cannot be any space between the brackets and the `|`s.
 An object type **must** begin with a key, so the `{|` would not have ambiguity. Further while you can have leading `|` in type definitions: `type A = | X | Y;` You cannot end a type with a `|`, so `|}` at the end of the object would not be ambiguous either.
 
All other `|` would still imply a union of types.

### Semantics for Interfaces

Marking an interface as exact would force any implementation to not have any addition keys. It is *not*, however, a fixed interface as you can still choose more specific values for your keys.

```ts
interface Pets {
  pets: Animal[];
}
class CatLoverPets implements Exact<Pets> {
  pets: Cat[];
}
// with new syntax:
interface Pets {|
  pets: Animal[];
|}
```

### Semantics for Unions

```ts
Exact<A | B | C> = Exact<A> | Exact<B> | Exact<C>;
```

### How do exact and inexact object flow from each other

This has been described before:

Passing an exact object when an inexact object is expected would be allowed.

Passing an inexact object when an exact object is expected would give you a type error since there could be extra keys and Typescript would warn you of that.

### What happens when using `T & U`?

```ts
type T = Exact<{name: string}>
type U = Exact<{age: number}>
type Combined = T & U;
// Combined == {name: string & never, age: number & never} == never
```

If `T` and `U` are exact object types, and don't have the exact same keys, then `T & U` should automatically be considered a `never` type as it is a type that is impossible. Two objects that don't allow addition keys can't also simultaneously have extra keys.

To make this even friendlier, when defining `Combined`, `T & U` could give a type error and warn you that it is an impossible type rather than waiting to find out later.

### Other Optional Types that are not Object Types?

Are not relevant here and should be discussed separately.

### Usecases?

There are many many use cases here. Anytime an object is JSON stringified or coded into a string in any other way, we don't want extra keys in our objects showing up. So here is an incomplete list of cases:

- An API library that allows you to set headers for a set of pre-defined keys. Allowing extra object keys would let the user set headers they're not allowed to and create problems.

- A React component where you want to accept a list of common HTML attributes but purposely exclude some other attributes (maybe you don't want any event listeners `onClick` etc, but want to allow any other regular props). If you simply take an object and spread it on the html element, Typescript will allow the extra props.

- A function that wants to take CSS styles but only for a few specific properties. Perhaps I want to create a function that lets you customize the colors only. If you allow extra keys, someone could pass in margin/height etc and typescript simply wouldn't give me an error.

- A [blog post](https://fettblog.eu/typescript-match-the-exact-object-shape/) the describes a hack to you can use today, but only for function input and you are forced to add a generic

The simple fact is that whenever reading objects, Typescript currently forces you to read each key manually rather than be able to use the object itself, because you never know when there might be extra data lurking within your object. Adding exact object types would solve it.

### Prior Art

Flow handles exact object correctly for a while now. By default you can use the syntax `{| name: string |}` to define an exact object. But you can opt-into a setting that make all object types exact by default and you can make an object inexact by using `{name: string, ...}`

Interfaces cannot be made exact.

