function h(r: Rec) {
  return _.map(r, (v) => fv(v)); // no error
}
```

But that's only because the typing of most lodash "Collection" functions is incorrect (and thankfully so, or we would need to check or assert the parameter type in each and every iteratee function!):
```
const c = { A: 1, B: 2, C: 'a' };
const r: Rec = c;
h(r); // `fv` will be called with a parameter which is not of type `V`
```

Second, I'd like to clear what I believe are some misconceptions I found in @goldingdamien's message:

> Exact types are just a way to detect extra properties.

This is incorrect. Exact types are a way to know the type of an object's keys.

> it's assumed that a type `T & U` is always assignable to `T`, but this fails if `T` is an exact type

Of course, this is pure set algebra: `&` is the intersection of types, and values in it are in either type.

If this fails, it means that the intersection was evaluated incorrectly. Some specific examples:

`Exact<{a : 1}> & {b: 2}` is just `void` -- all it's values (it has none) are assignable to either type.

`Exact<{a: 1}> & {b?: 2}` is `Exact<{a: 1}>`, and its values are assignable to either type.

_(In the following discussion, `{...T, ...U}` is the type of `{...t, ...u}` where `t` is a `T` and `u` is a `U`)_

I believe the confusion stems from the fact that `T & U` is typically used to mean `{...T, ...U}`, which is only true for non-exact object types. In other words, `Exact<T> & Exact<U>` is NOT `Exact<T & U>`.

> Is `{ s: "hello", n: 3 }` assignable to `{ s: string } | Exact<{ n: number }>`? "Yes" seems like the wrong answer because whoever looks for `n` and finds it won't be happy to see `s` [...]

Once again, this is just set algebra, with the union of types in this case, and thus "Yes" is the correct answer. Whoever is not to be happy to see an `s` should request an `Exact<{ n: number }>`, not an `{ s: string } | Exact<{ n: number }>`.

> The "right" type is arguably { type: "name", firstName: string, lastName: string, age: undefined } | { type: "age", years: number, firstName: undefined, lastName: undefined }

Actually, `Exact<T>` is precisely `{...{[string|number]: never}, ...T }`.

So we just need spread types and we'd get exact types for free (assuming correctness elsewhere).

